record_data.record_plain_text: 1. Availability. Seller will make wholesale electric energy, capacity, and ancillary services available under this Tariff to any purchaser, except as prohibited below. 2. Applicability. This Tariff is applicable to all sales of energy, capacity, and ancillary services by Seller not otherwise subject to a particular rate schedule of Seller. 3. Rates. All sales shall be made at the rates established between the purchaser and Seller. 4. Other Terms and Conditions. All other terms and conditions shall be established by agreement between the purchaser and Seller. 5. Compliance with Commission Regulations. Seller shall comply with the provisions of 18 C.F.R. Part 35, Subpart H, as applicable, and with any conditions the Commission imposes in its orders concerning Seller’s market-based rate authority, including orders in which the Commission authorizes Seller to engage in affiliate sales under this Tariff or otherwise restricts or limits the Seller’s market-based rate authority. Failure to comply with the applicable provisions of 18 C.F.R. Part 35, Subpart H, and with any orders of the Commission concerning Seller’s market-based rate authority, will constitute a violation of this Tariff. 6. Limitations and Exemptions Regarding Market Based Rate Authority. Seller does not have any limitations on its market-based rate authority except as otherwise provided in this Tariff. The Commission granted Seller in Olympus Phase 1, LLC, Docket No. ER25-____-000 the following waivers and blanket authorization: (a) waiver of Subparts B and C of Part 35 of the Commission’s regulations requiring the filing of cost-of-service information, except for sections 35.12(a), 35.13(b), 35.15 and 35.16; (b) waiver of the requirements of Part 41 and Part 101, with the exception that waiver of the provisions of Part 101 that apply to hydropower licensees is not granted with respect to licensed hydropower projects; (c) waiver of Part 141 of the Commission’s regulations concerning accounting and reporting requirements, with the exception of 18 C.F.R. § 141.15; and (d) blanket approval as to Section 204 of the FPA and Part 34 of the Commission’s regulations for all future issuances of securities and debt and assumption of liabilities. 7. Ancillary Services. PJM: Seller offers regulation and frequency response service, energy imbalance service, and operating reserve service (which includes spinning, 10-minute, and 30-minute reserves) for sale into the market administered by PJM Interconnection, L.L.C. (“PJM”) and, where the PJM Open Access Transmission Tariff permits, the self-supply of these services to purchasers for a bilateral sale that is used to satisfy the ancillary services requirements of the PJM Office of Interconnection. New York: Seller offers regulation and frequency response service, and operating reserve service (which include 10-minute non-synchronous, 30-minute operating reserves, 10-minute spinning reserves, and 10-minute non-spinning reserves) for sale to purchasers in the market administered by the New York Independent System Operator, Inc. New England: Seller offers regulation and frequency response service (automatic generator control), operating reserve service (which includes 10-minute spinning reserve, 10-minute non-spinning reserve, and 30-minute operating reserve service) to purchasers within the markets administered by the ISO New England, Inc. California: Seller offers regulation service, spinning reserve service, and non-spinning reserve service to the California Independent System Operator Corporation (“CAISO”) and to others that are self-supplying ancillary services to the CAISO. MISO: Seller offers regulation service and operating reserve service (which include 10-minute spinning reserve and 10-minute supplemental reserve) for sale to the Midcontinent Independent System Operator, Inc. (MISO) and to others that are self-supplying ancillary services to MISO. Southwest Power Pool: Seller offers regulation service and operating reserve service (which include 10-minute spinning reserve and 10-minute supplemental reserve) for sale to the Southwest Power Pool, Inc. (SPP) and to others that are self-supplying ancillary services to SPP. Third-party ancillary services: Seller offers Regulation Service, Reactive Supply and Voltage Control Service, Energy and Generator Imbalance Service, Operating Reserve-Spinning, Operating Reserve-Supplemental, and Primary Frequency Response Service. Sales will not include the following: (1) sales to an RTO or an ISO, i.e., where that entity has no ability to self-supply ancillary services but instead depends on third parties; and (2) sales to a traditional, franchised public utility affiliated with the third-party supplier, or sales where the underlying transmission service is on the system of the public utility affiliated with the third-party supplier. Sales of Operating Reserve-Spinning and Operating Reserve-Supplemental will not include sales to a public utility that is purchasing ancillary services to satisfy its own open access transmission tariff requirements to offer ancillary services to its own customers, except where the Commission has granted authorization. Sales of Regulation Service and Reactive Supply and Voltage Control Service will not include sales to a public utility that is purchasing ancillary services to satisfy its own open access transmission tariff requirements to offer ancillary services to its own customers, except at rates not to exceed the buying public utility transmission provider’s OATT rate for the same service or where the Commission has granted authorization. 8. Seller Category. Seller is a Category 2 Seller in the Southwest region and a Category 1 Seller in the Central, Southeast, Northwest, Northeast, and Southwest Power Pool regions, as defined by 18 C.F.R. § 35.36(a). 9. Effective Date. This Tariff is effective on the date specified by the Commission. This Tariff shall continue in effect until terminated or changed in accordance with any applicable regulatory requirements.

Upstream is developing a combined solar photovoltaic (“PV”) array and battery energy storage system (“BESS”) to be constructed in Salome, Arizona, consisting of, among other things: (i) 129 Sungrow SG4400 PV Inverter Units rated at 3.955 MW and 45 C; (ii) 318 Tesla Megapack 2 XL 4 Hour Inverter Units (Built into the BESS) at 0.85 MW and 45 C; (iii) associated infrastructure and step-up transformers; (iv) meters and metering equipment (v) appropriate amount of static and dynamic reactive resources to provide 0.95 power factor and (vi) the maximum auxiliary loads are approximately 1.095 Mva (3 x 150 kVa BESS aux. transformer, 129 x 5 kVa auxiliary supply on PV inverters), and PV parasitic loads are 0.986 MW. The maximum total net output of the Project at the Point of Interconnection is 500 MW (hereinafter, the “Centennial Flats Solar and BESS Project” or “Project”). B. The Centennial Flats Solar and BESS Project will be divided into three phases where Olympus 1, Olympus 2, and Olympus 3 (collectively, the “Olympus Entities” and each an “Olympus Entity”), will develop, and/or its permitted successors and assigns hereunder, are (or will be) developing, and plan to construct, own and operate one or more solar PV generating and/or BESS projects and related facilities (collectively, the “Owner’s Projects” and each individually, an “Owner’s Project”). C. To avoid the costly duplication of facilities necessary to transmit the output of each Owner respective Owner’s Project to the Cielo Azul Switchyard, the Owners are jointly developing and intend to share certain costs and ownership of certain gen-tie and substation facilities described on Exhibit A-2 (as the same may be modified and supplemented as permitted herein, collectively, “Shared Facilities”). The Shared Facilities will be co-owned and shared by the Owners as provided herein. Upstream will have no ownership interest in the Shared Facilities. The Owner’s Projects are contemplated to interconnect and deliver energy in an amount up to the Maximum Interconnection Capacity for the Shared Facilities, to the Cielo Azul Switchyard. D. Olympus 1 plans to develop a combined solar photovoltaic array and BESS to be constructed in Salome, Arizona, consisting of, among other things: a 166.667 MW AC solar PV facility (226,183.300 kW DC) with bifacial polycrystalline modules mounted on NexTracker Horizon single-axis tracker racking, collocated with an 89.116 MW 4-hour battery energy storage facility with lithium-ion battery energy storage. The Owner’s Project is interconnecting at 500 kV to the new Cielo Azul Switchyard located adjacent to Project’s western boundary. E. Olympus 2 plans to develop a combined solar photovoltaic array and BESS to be constructed in Salome, Arizona, consisting of, among other things: a 166.667 MW AC solar {00653487;1} -1- PV facility (225,205.650 kW DC) with bifacial polycrystalline modules mounted on NexTracker Horizon single-axis tracker racking, collocated with an 89.116 MW 4-hour battery energy storage facility with lithium-ion battery energy storage. The Owner’s Project is interconnecting at 500 kV to the new Cielo Azul Switchyard located adjacent to Project’s western boundary. F. Olympus 3 plans to develop a combined solar photovoltaic array and BESS to be constructed in Salome, Arizona, consisting of, among other things : a 166.666 MW AC solar PV facility (222,867.450 kW DC) with bifacial polycrystalline modules mounted on NexTracker Horizon single-axis tracker racking, collocated with an 89.116 MW 4-hour battery energy storage facility with lithium-ion battery energy storage. The Owner’s Project is interconnecting at 500 kV to the new Cielo Azul Switchyard located adjacent to Project’s western boundary. G. The Olympus Entities have equal ownership of Upstream as its sole members and holders of 100% of its issued and outstanding membership interests. Upstream executed six Power Purchase Agreements (“PPA”) with the ability to assign to a specified Olympus Entity provided that certain conditions are satisfied, including that the Olympus Entities and Upstream enter into a sublease for co-tenancy in the Project site. Upstream and Arizona State Land Department (“ASLD”) entered into a lease dated April 26, 2023 (the “Master Lease.”) Under the Master Lease, ASLD leases approximately 4800 contiguous acres (the “Parcel”) to Upstream to develop, construct, operate and maintain one or more solar PV and BESS facilities. Since the Master Lease does not permit partial assignment, Upstream is the lessee under the Master Lease and sublets to the Olympus Entities, pursuant to that certain Sublease Agreement by and among Upstream, Olympus 1, Olympus 2, and Olympus 3 executed on the date hereof (the “Sublease Agreement.”) Pursuant to the Sublease Agreement, Upstream has subleased the entire Parcel to the Olympus Entities as co-tenants with each holding an undivided (1/3) interest in and to the subleasehold estate created thereunder. The Olympus Entities have or will enter into a separate tenancy-in-common agreement between themselves that governs the allocation of specific rights and obligations under the Sublease Agreement, including, without limitation, the identification of portions of the Parcel intended for the exclusive use of each Olympus Entity for purposes of the development, construction, ownership, operation, and maintenance of each Olympus Entity’s respective Project Controlled Assets. H. Upstream entered into a Large Generator Interconnection Agreement (“LGIA”), dated January 5, 2023, by and among Upstream, DCR Transmission, LLC, and CAISO, which provides for the interconnection and delivery of up to 500 MW (as measured at the Point of Interconnection) of energy from the Centennial Flats Solar and BESS Project to the 500 kV bus at the Cielo Azul Switchyard. Upstream assigned its rights and obligations as Interconnection Customer under the LGIA to the Olympus Entities pursuant to that certain Assignment and Assumption Agreement dated as of the date hereof. Upstream, the Olympus Entities, CAISO and DCR Transmission, LLC will amend and restate the LGIA to contemplate this Agreement. I. Olympus 1 has contracted for the construction of the Shared Facilities pursuant to the HV EPC Agreement, and each of the other Owners will reimburse or directly pay for its Proportionate Share of the total Construction Costs as set forth herein. J. Upstream shall be the initial “Shared Facilities Manager” subject to its right to resign, whereafter the successor Shared Facilities Manager shall be selected by the Owners Committee. The Shared Facilities Manager shall be authorized and shall exercise commercially {00653487;1} -2- reasonable efforts to comply with Section 4.2 herein (Powers and Duties of Shared Facilities Manager) on behalf of each of the Owners. K. Pursuant to (i) the Common Real Property Documents (defined herein) and (ii) those certain partial assignment and assumption or other agreements which may, in the future, be entered into by and between the Owners, each Owner holds or will hold its Shared Facilities Ownership Percentage as tenants-in-common in the Shared Facilities. In furtherance thereof, the Owners wish to set forth certain of their rights and responsibilities in respect of the development, construction and operation of the Shared Facilities necessary for the Owner’s Projects. L. Each of the Owners expects to transmit electric energy generated from its respective Owner’s Project to the Cielo Azul Switchyard by sharing the use and ownership of the Shared Facilities.
